      "note": "According to several Traditions (extensively quoted by Ibn Kathir), they played, with a derisive intent, upon the word hittah, substituting for it something irrelevant or meaningless. Muhammad 'Abduh, however, is of the opinion that the \"saying\" referred to in verse 58 is merely a metaphor for an attitude of mind demanded of them, and that, correspondingly, the \"substitution\" signifies here a wilful display of arrogance in disregard of God's command (see Manar I, 324 f.)."
